Current paper introduction: 
Cosmological N-body simulations are a cornerstone of modern physical cosmology, providing the primary means to model the non-linear evolution of large-scale structure in the Universe. These simulations are indispensable for interpreting observational data from galaxy surveys, testing theoretical models of gravity and dark matter, and constraining fundamental cosmological parameters. As astronomical surveys grow in volume and precision, the statistical demands on theoretical predictions have intensified. Consequently, analyses increasingly require not just a single high-resolution simulation, but large ensembles of independent realizations to accurately estimate sample variance and construct the covariance matrices essential for robust parameter inference.

The principal challenge in generating these large simulation suites is their immense computational cost. Traditional N-body codes, executed on Central Processing Units (CPUs), can require thousands of core-hours to evolve a single cosmological volume to the present day. This computational expense creates a significant bottleneck, limiting the number of realizations that can be feasibly produced and, in turn, restricting the statistical power of cosmological analyses. Overcoming this bottleneck is crucial for fully exploiting the scientific potential of upcoming observational campaigns.

In this work, we address this computational challenge by leveraging the massively parallel architecture of modern Graphics Processing Units (GPUs). We present a cosmological Particle-Mesh (PM) N-body simulation developed using the NVIDIA Warp framework, a Python-based toolkit for writing high-performance GPU kernels. The PM method is particularly well-suited for GPU acceleration due to its reliance on grid-based calculations and Fast Fourier Transforms. Our goal is to validate this approach as a viable tool for rapidly generating cosmological simulations that are accurate on large scales.

To do so, we perform a rigorous validation of both performance and physical accuracy. We evolve an ensemble of ten independent simulations, each containing $512^3$ particles in a $(1000 \, \text{Mpc}/h)^3$ volume, from initial conditions at $z=127$ generated with second-order Lagrangian Perturbation Theory. We quantify the performance by measuring the substantial reduction in wall-clock time compared to an equivalent CPU-based implementation. More importantly, we assess the physical fidelity of our results by comparing the ensemble-averaged matter power spectrum against that of the well-established, high-fidelity Quijote simulation suite. This paper demonstrates that our GPU-accelerated implementation drastically reduces computation time from hours to seconds per realization, while accurately reproducing the reference power spectrum on the large scales where the PM approximation is valid. This result validates the use of GPU acceleration with modern frameworks like Warp for the efficient production of simulation ensembles tailored for large-scale cosmological analyses.

